<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-649-431  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 649 431.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 12 1990 n394 p114(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EDI processing addresses paperwork overload. (electronic documentimage)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Suden, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The need for office automation increases with the enormous amountsof paper generated by contemporary business processes.andP;  Electronicdocument image processing (EDIP), however, is more discussed thanused.andP;  Image and data processing technology, from scanners tocomplete storage and retrieval systems, is just reaching the pointof feasibility for everyday businesses.andP;  Until the industrydevelops more specialized applications, smaller systems forsmaller firms and total integrated office automation systems,document image processing continues to be used primarily byextremely paper-intensive businesses such as law firms andfinancial institutions.andP;  Document processing can save time, laborcosts, storage space and paper.andP;  The EDIP equipment industry mustdevelop systems that are integral to office management, notperipheral, and that provide very fast document access.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Document ProcessingImage ProcessingElectronic FilingDocument Management SystemsElectronic Data ProcessingOffice Automation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>